"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132252","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-06-24","<p>Future funding for local authorities’ public health responsibilities will be considered carefully in the next spending review, taking full account of the available evidence.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-06-24T16:48:38.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132252/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132252/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-06-14","Public Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans he has to increase public health funding for local authorities.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","264774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132253","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-06-24","<p>In November 2017, the joint DWP/DHSC Work and Health Unit (WHU) published Improving Lives: the Future of Work, Health and Disability setting out our response to Thriving at Work and WHU is now overseeing progress across 40 recommendations. The Civil Service is committed to being a leading employer and implementing the core and enhanced mental health standards to deliver lasting cultural change. All main government departments have benchmarked themselves against the mental health standards to identify best practice and areas requiring further action, and every Civil Service Permanent Secretary now has a performance objective directly related to implementing the standards and Civil Service Wellbeing Confident Leaders training is being rolled out to senior leaders.</p><p> </p><p>One of the review’s recommendations was about transparency as a significant opportunity to encourage cultural change around mental health. We have worked with partners, including employers, to develop a framework to support organisations to record and voluntarily report information on disability and mental health in the workplace. This framework was published on 22<sup>nd</sup> November 2018 and is aimed at large employers with 250 or more employees. The WHU is an active member of the Thriving at Work Leadership Council consisting of a range of business and public sector representatives, and leading trade associations. The council is an employer led group that will continue to meet throughout 2019 with the primary objectives to champion the mental health standards and explore innovative solutions to further drive their implementation and adoption. Individual members committed to promoting the standards through their networks and to create sector champions.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-06-24T12:17:50.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132253/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132253/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-14","Employment: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department is taking to implement the six core standards for workplaces as set out in the Government’s thriving at work report; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Sir George Howarth","264730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132254","Home Office","false","2019-06-19","<p>In December 2018, the Government set out its proposals in “the UK’s future Skills-based Immigration System” White Paper. The White Paper proposals include a new route for skilled workers which will be open to anyone at RQF level 3 and above, irrespective of where they are applying from. The White Paper is clear that those applying in this route will be subject to an assessment of their language skills in order to support integration.</p><p>The Shortage Occupation List (SOL), is based on expert advice from the Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) and identifies those occupations deemed to be in national shortage. It does not include a separate language assessment. The MAC published their most recent review of the full SOL on the 29 May. The Government is grateful to the MAC for a comprehensive report, the content of which we are now considering.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","264762","2019-06-19T13:39:52.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132254/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132254/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-06-14","Migrant Workers: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how language competency will be taken into account as a key skill in the skilled workers route under a new immigration framework.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","264761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132255","Home Office","false","2019-06-19","<p>In December 2018, the Government set out its proposals in “the UK’s future Skills-based Immigration System” White Paper. The White Paper proposals include a new route for skilled workers which will be open to anyone at RQF level 3 and above, irrespective of where they are applying from. The White Paper is clear that those applying in this route will be subject to an assessment of their language skills in order to support integration.</p><p>The Shortage Occupation List (SOL), is based on expert advice from the Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) and identifies those occupations deemed to be in national shortage. It does not include a separate language assessment. The MAC published their most recent review of the full SOL on the 29 May. The Government is grateful to the MAC for a comprehensive report, the content of which we are now considering.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","264761","2019-06-19T13:39:52.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132255/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132255/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-06-14","Migrant Workers: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of a language competency for the shortage occupation list under the proposed new immigration framework.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","264762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132256","Home Office","false","2019-06-19","<p>The Government published its White Paper “The UK’s future skills-based immigration system” on 19 December 2018, which proposed a new route for short-term workers to come to the UK for up to 12 months. This will be subject to a full review by 2025.</p><p><br>In the interim, we have launched a year-long programme of engagement to enable businesses and other stakeholders to shape the final details of policy and processes contained within the White Paper.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-06-19T13:41:46.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132256/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132256/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-06-14","Visas: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will make it his policy to extend the proposed transitional measure of a time-limited route for temporary short-term workers from 12 months to three years.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","264763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132257","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-06-19","<p>As at 14<sup>th</sup> June 2019, the Department has spent £131,399.50 on legal costs defending and appealing the cases in relation to people formerly in receipt of Severe Disability premium that have transferred to Universal Credit, broken down as follows<em>.</em></p><p> </p><p>The Department has spent £91,528.68 on legal costs defending and appealing the case of <em>TP and AR v SSWP.</em> The Department has spent £39,870.82 on legal costs defending and appealing the case of <em>TP, AR and SXC v SSWP.</em> These figures include Government Legal Department litigation fees, counsel’s fees and other disbursements, as well as VAT where payable. This does not include payment of any costs paid or which may be owed to the claimants’ solicitors.</p><p> </p><p>Time spent by Government advisory lawyers is not recorded in a manner that allows it to be attributed to individual cases. Time spent by policy officials supporting lawyers is not recorded.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","264776","2019-06-19T16:04:58.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132257/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132257/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-14","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much her Department has spent from the public purse on defending legal cases in relation to people formerly in receipt of severe disability premium that have transferred to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","264775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132258","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-06-19","<p>As at 14<sup>th</sup> June 2019, the Department has spent £131,399.50 on legal costs defending and appealing the cases in relation to people formerly in receipt of Severe Disability premium that have transferred to Universal Credit, broken down as follows<em>.</em></p><p> </p><p>The Department has spent £91,528.68 on legal costs defending and appealing the case of <em>TP and AR v SSWP.</em> The Department has spent £39,870.82 on legal costs defending and appealing the case of <em>TP, AR and SXC v SSWP.</em> These figures include Government Legal Department litigation fees, counsel’s fees and other disbursements, as well as VAT where payable. This does not include payment of any costs paid or which may be owed to the claimants’ solicitors.</p><p> </p><p>Time spent by Government advisory lawyers is not recorded in a manner that allows it to be attributed to individual cases. Time spent by policy officials supporting lawyers is not recorded.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","264775","2019-06-19T16:04:58.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132258/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132258/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-14","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much her Department has spent to date on legal costs in the case of R (TP AR & SXC) v SSWP & Anor [2019] EWHC 1116 (QB) involving payments to former recipients of Severe Disability Premium who have transferred to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","264776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132259","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-06-19","As at 14th June 2019, the Department has spent £52,446 on legal costs defending and appealing the case of Johnson &amp; Others v SSWP. This includes Government Legal Department litigation fees, counsel’s fees and other disbursements, as well as VAT where payable. This does not include payment of the claimants’ solicitor’s costs. Time spent by Government advisory lawyers is not recorded in a manner that allows it to be attributed to individual cases. ","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2019-06-19T13:58:43.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132259/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1132259/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-14","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much her Department has spent on legal costs in the case of R (Johnson and Ors) v SSWP [2019] EWHC 23 (Admin) as of 14 June 2019.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","264777"
