"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131637","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-06-20","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not hold a detailed record of the cost of advertising changes to men and women’s State Pension age since the passage of the Pensions Act 1995. The Department has previously provided information to the House of Commons in a multitude of ways that clearly demonstrate the extensive steps the Department of Social Security and then the Department for Work and Pensions, took to communicate State Pension age changes at a significant cost to those departments.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2019-06-20T14:00:55.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131637/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131637/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-12","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much her Department has spent on advertising the state pension age increase for women.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","263828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131638","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-06-17","<p>The information requested is provided in the tables attached with this answer. These tables include data, covering the period 2007 – 2018, on:</p><ul><li>The number of offenders with a specified number of previous convictions who were convicted of an offence and not sentenced to immediate custody.</li><li>The number of offenders with a specified number of previous convictions who were convicted of an offence and sentenced to immediate custody.</li></ul>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","263848","2019-06-17T16:52:07.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131638/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131638/answer","Copy of 263829 and 263848 Response Table.xlsx","Copy of 263829 and 263848 Response Table.xlsx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131638/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-06-12","Convictions: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people who previously had (a) no, (b) between one and four, (c) between five and nine, (d) between 10 and 15, (e) between 16 and 25, (f) between 26 and 50, (g) between 51 and 75, (h) between 76 and 100 and (i) 101 or more convictions, were convicted in each of the years since 2007, but did not receive an immediate custodial sentence.","false","Biography information for Neil O'Brien","Harborough","Neil O'Brien","263829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131639","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-21","<p>In 2017, we provided financial support to local authorities for data collection and reporting on cladding on high rise private residential buildings, on recognition of this as a new burden. The total amount transferred to local authorities was £289,000. Government then announced on 1 May 2018 that it would provide financial support of £1 million to assist those local authorities most affected in identifying private sector residential buildings over 18 metres to complete the process. The total allocation was paid to 80 eligible local authorities last summer.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","263711 ; 263712","2019-06-21T10:53:57.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131639/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131639/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-12","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Building Safety Programme monthly data release of 31 May 2019, how many local authorities have received the allowance for authorities for identifying the cladding and insulation status of private sector buildings.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","263710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131640","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-06-21","<p>In 2017, we provided financial support to local authorities for data collection and reporting on cladding on high rise private residential buildings, on recognition of this as a new burden. The total amount transferred to local authorities was £289,000. Government then announced on 1 May 2018 that it would provide financial support of £1 million to assist those local authorities most affected in identifying private sector residential buildings over 18 metres to complete the process. The total allocation was paid to 80 eligible local authorities last summer.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","263710 ; 263712","2019-06-21T10:53:57.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131640/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131640/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-12","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Building Safety Programme: Monthly Data Release of 31 May 2019, what amount of the allowance for local authorities to identify the cladding and insulation status of private sector buildings has been given to local authorities.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","263711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131641","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-06-20","<p>Any publicly available resources we have used to inform our analysis of the proposals in the consultation will be made available with the Government response.</p><p> </p><p>Various respondents to the consultation on cleaner domestic burning of solid fuels and wood sent in their own price analyses of fuels. These note that there are price differentials associated with volumes purchased, and seasonality as well as between differing locations across England. Research has been undertaken based on these responses along with further analysis of advertised retail prices to assess the effect of the proposals in the consultation.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","263781","2019-06-20T10:17:38.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131641/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131641/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-06-12","Solid Fuels: Heating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the consultation on cleaner domestic burning of solid fuels and wood in England, if he will deposit in the Library copies of all reports and datasets his Department is aware of on non PM2.5 toxic pollutants released when burning (a) smokeless briquettes, (b) wet wood, (c) dried wood and (d) house coal on open domestic fires; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","263780"
